rse was the image forming in my mind. <BR>  <BR> Seattle Slew, Secretariat, Man-o-War were names that started swirling around in my head. I knew from the naming conventions that they wouldn't be accepted. Then my memories came to the Triple Crown winner named Affirmed. <BR>  <BR> Now Affirmed sounded like a great paladin name, but doing a little research I found that while Affirmed won the Triple Crown, one horse finished second to him in all three of those races. That horse's name? Why of course it was Alydar. The horse that would have been the Triple Crown winner if there were no Affirmed. <BR>  <BR> So after a little letter manipulation, I came up with the name Alidaar. <BR>  <BR> At level 20, I stayed with the horse theme. Cavonnier wasn't a Triple Crown winner, I think all he ever did was show in one Triple Crown race. It was the only thoroughbred name I could find, however, that fit in as a last name.  <BR>  <BR> Alidaar Cavonnier <BR> Paladin of Tunare <BR> Karana <BR>  <BR>  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Rebel Namer</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/29/00 10:00:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgodsmightroleplaytavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Replay's blatant violation of the naming rules</span><hr size=1> We have all seen the latest post on EQ naming rules... and I hope most of us are in agreement that they are a little obsurd.  I have decided that in my protest to the rules, I will target everyone's favorite Paladin, Replay. <BR>  <BR> Sorry, Sir, but your name is in blatant violation of the naming rules.  Your first name is modern and has no place in this fantasy world.  Equally disqualifying is the fact that it is a copyrighted, and trademarked, name.  As for your last name, I f